Steps to Upgrade Python on RHEL 8 via SSH (using PuTTY)
Login to the Remote Server Using PuTTY:

Open PuTTY.
Enter the hostname or IP address of your remote RHEL 8 server in the "Host Name" field.
Click "Open" to start the SSH session.
Enter your username and password when prompted.
Update System Repositories:

Once logged in, it's a good practice to update your package list. Run the following command:

bash
Copy code
sudo dnf update
Enable the EPEL Repository:

The Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux (EPEL) repository may be required to install additional Python packages:

bash
Copy code
sudo dnf install epel-release
Enable the codeready-builder Repository:

This repository provides additional packages required by developers:

bash
Copy code
sudo subscription-manager repos --enable codeready-builder-for-rhel-8-x86_64-rpms
Install Python 3.11:

Use the Software Collections (SCL) to install Python 3.11 without interfering with the system's default Python version:

bash
Copy code
sudo dnf module reset python39  # Reset if needed
sudo dnf module install python3.11
Verify the installation:

bash
Copy code
python3.11 --version
Set Up Python 3.11 as the Default (Optional):

If you want to use Python 3.11 as the default Python version for your shell sessions, you can create an alias:

bash
Copy code
echo 'alias python=python3.11' >> ~/.bashrc
echo 'alias pip=pip3.11' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
Alternatively, use update-alternatives:

bash
Copy code
sudo update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/python3 python3 /usr/bin/python3.11 2
sudo update-alternatives --config python3
Install Development Tools:

These tools are needed for building and compiling Python packages:

bash
Copy code
sudo dnf groupinstall 'development tools'
sudo dnf install python3.11-devel openssl-devel bzip2-devel libffi-devel
Create and Activate a Virtual Environment:

It's a best practice to use virtual environments to avoid conflicts between different projects:

bash
Copy code
python3.11 -m venv myenv
source myenv/bin/activate
Check the Python version within the virtual environment:

bash
Copy code
python --version
Install Required Python Packages:

Inside the virtual environment, use pip to install any required Python packages:

bash
Copy code
pip install <package-name>
